{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01E9C39fy1rdnMXULmeGq5BY","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Mendelson Kornblum Orthopedic & Spine Specialists — Product Research\n     2→\n     3→Researched: 2026-02-14\n     4→Developer website: http://www.mendelsonortho.com/ (redirects to https://synergyhealth.org/)\n     5→\n     6→## Overview\n     7→\n     8→Mendelson Kornblum Orthopedic & Spine Specialists (MKO) is a multi-location orthopedic practice group in Southeast Michigan, founded in 1963 by Dr. Herbert Mendelson. The practice has grown from a small family orthopedic office specializing in spine, neck, and back pain into a large musculoskeletal care organization with over 20 physicians across multiple locations (Livonia, Sterling Heights, Southfield, Port Huron, and others). The practice has rebranded under the umbrella of **Synergy Health Partners** (SHP), which is described as \"Michigan's only integrated musculoskeletal care provider.\" MKO remains the premier orthopedic practice within SHP. The Mendelson family continues in leadership — three sons of the founder (David, Jeffrey, and Stephen Mendelson) are orthopedic surgeons who co-own and manage the practice along with Dr. Martin Kornblum.\n     9→\n    10→OrthoplexEMR is a **custom-built, single-organization EMR** — it was developed specifically for MKO/SHP and is not a commercially sold product. The mandatory disclosures page explicitly states \"there are currently no plans for its sale.\" The EMR was built by **Proactive Technology Management**, a small managed IT services company based in Bingham Farms, Michigan (Metro Detroit), which is co-founded and owned by **Michael Weinberger**. Weinberger serves as CTO of both Proactive Technology Management and Synergy Health Partners MSO, LLC, making him the technical architect for both the IT infrastructure and the EMR. The CHPL contact, **Jurgen B. Jansen** (jjansen@synergyhealth.org), is an IT Project Manager at SynergyHealth. This is an unusually tight coupling between a clinical practice, its IT services provider, and its certified EMR — essentially an in-house software project.\n    11→\n    12→## Product: OrthoplexEMR\n    13→\n    14→CHPL ID: 9349\n    15→CHPL Product Number: 15.04.04.3014.Orth.01.00.1.180101\n    16→Certification Date: 2018-01-01\n    17→\n    18→### What It Is\n    19→\n    20→OrthoplexEMR is a proprietary, custom-built electronic medical records application developed by Proactive Technology Management for use exclusively by Mendelson Kornblum Orthopedic & Spine Specialists / Synergy Health Partners. It is certified as a complete Health IT Module with a broad set of ONC certifications covering clinical data management, care transitions, patient portal, public health reporting, and FHIR APIs.\n    21→\n    22→The certified product is the entire EMR — there is no separate commercial product suite. The SED (Safety-enhanced Design) intended user description is simply \"Orthopedic Clinc\" [sic], confirming the narrow target audience.\n    23→\n    24→### Users & Market\n    25→\n    26→- **Single customer**: MKO/Synergy Health Partners. This is not a commercial EMR product.\n    27→- **End users**: Orthopedic surgeons, spine specialists, pain management physicians, podiatrists, and clinical staff at MKO/SHP locations across Southeast Michigan.\n    28→- **Setting**: Multi-site orthopedic practice group with 20+ physicians, including outpatient clinics, physical/occupational therapy sites, MRI imaging centers, and ambulatory surgery centers.\n    29→- **No commercial market**: The disclosure page states there are no plans to sell the software.\n    30→\n    31→### Modules & Functionality\n    32→\n    33→Because OrthoplexEMR is a custom in-house product, there is very limited public documentation of its features beyond what can be inferred from its ONC certification criteria and required dependencies. The product does not have a marketing website, feature pages, or third-party reviews.\n    34→\n    35→**What the certification criteria tell us:**\n    36→- **(a)(1)–(a)(5)**: CPOE for medications, labs, imaging; drug-drug/drug-allergy interaction checks; demographics; vital signs; problem list — standard clinical documentation capabilities\n    37→- **(a)(12)**: Family health history\n    38→- **(a)(14)**: Implantable device list — particularly relevant for an orthopedic practice performing joint replacements\n    39→- **(b)(1)–(b)(3)**: Transitions of care, clinical information reconciliation — C-CDA document generation and consumption\n    40→- **(b)(10)–(b)(11)**: EHI export and care plan functionality\n    41→- **(c)(1)–(c)(3)**: Clinical quality measures — specifically CMS50v6, CMS68v7, CMS123v6, CMS134v6, CMS138v6, CMS139v6 (covering referrals, medication documentation, diabetes care, chronic kidney disease, tobacco, and falls screening)\n    42→- **(e)(1), (e)(3)**: Patient portal / view-download-transmit; patient health information capture\n    43→- **(f)(1), (f)(4)**: Immunization registry and syndromic surveillance public health reporting\n    44→- **(g)(3)–(g)(7), (g)(9)–(g)(10)**: Safety-enhanced design, quality management, accessibility, consolidated CDA creation, application access, and FHIR API access\n    45→- **(h)(1)**: Direct Project messaging\n    46→\n    47→**Required dependencies (from mandatory disclosures):**\n    48→- **MDToolbox**: E-prescribing module (electronic prescribing, EPCS, prior authorization). This tells us prescribing workflows are not native to OrthoplexEMR — they use MDToolbox as an integrated third-party service.\n    49→- **EMRDirect**: Direct messaging HISP service for secure clinical data exchange (C-CDA transmission). This handles the (h)(1) Direct Project requirements.\n    50→- **e-IMO (Intelligent Medical Objects)**: Clinical terminology and vocabulary service. IMO provides clinician-friendly diagnosis terms mapped to ICD, SNOMED CT, and other code sets. This means the system uses IMO for problem list, diagnosis coding, and likely billing code selection.\n    51→- **SMTP (generic)**: Email integration for notifications and secure messaging.\n    52→\n    53→**What the EHI export page reveals about system content:**\n    54→The EHI export documentation describes C-CDA–based exports containing: demographics, encounters, medications, problems, allergies/adverse reactions, vital signs, care team information, immunizations, social history, medical equipment, test results, procedures, goals, health concerns, and treatment plans. This suggests these are the core clinical data domains the system manages.\n    55→\n    56→### Data & Content\n    57→\n    58→Based on the evidence gathered, OrthoplexEMR stores and manages:\n    59→\n    60→**Clinical data (confirmed by certification + EHI export page):**\n    61→- Patient demographics\n    62→- Problem lists / diagnoses (using IMO terminology mapped to ICD/SNOMED)\n    63→- Medication lists and prescribing data (via MDToolbox integration)\n    64→- Allergy and adverse reaction records\n    65→- Vital signs\n    66→- Encounter records\n    67→- Procedures\n    68→- Test/lab results\n    69→- Immunization records\n    70→- Social history\n    71→- Medical equipment / implantable devices (especially relevant for orthopedic implants)\n    72→- Care team information\n    73→- Goals, health concerns, and treatment plans\n    74→- Family health history\n    75→- Clinical quality measure data\n    76→\n    77→**Likely stored but not directly confirmed from public sources:**\n    78→- Clinical notes and documentation (implied by EMR use in a 20+ physician practice)\n    79→- Imaging orders and possibly results (certified for CPOE imaging orders; MKO operates MRI centers)\n    80→- Referral data (CMS50v6 is a referral measure)\n    81→- Patient portal messages and patient-submitted health information (certified for (e)(1) and (e)(3))\n    82→- Documents exchanged via Direct messaging (via EMRDirect)\n    83→\n    84→**Unclear / not confirmed:**\n    85→- **Billing and claims data**: The website and disclosures do not mention whether OrthoplexEMR includes billing/practice management functionality. Michael Weinberger's bio mentions expertise in \"medical billing, scheduling, and credentialing systems,\" and the intake portal (intake.mendelsonortho.com) exists as a separate system, suggesting the practice may use separate systems for scheduling, billing, and intake. It is unclear whether these functions are part of OrthoplexEMR or handled by separate software.\n    86→- **Scheduling**: The practice has a separate intake portal; scheduling may be separate from the EMR.\n    87→- **Imaging/PACS**: MKO operates MRI centers, but whether PACS data is integrated into OrthoplexEMR or managed separately is unknown.\n    88→- **Surgical records**: As an orthopedic surgery practice with ambulatory surgery centers, operative notes and surgical records are presumably part of the EMR, but this is not documented publicly.\n    89→- **Physical/occupational therapy records**: SHP includes PT/OT services; whether those notes are in OrthoplexEMR or a separate system is unknown.\n    90→\n    91→### Research Gaps\n    92→\n    93→This is an exceptionally difficult product to research because:\n    94→1. It is a custom in-house EMR with no commercial presence, marketing materials, or public feature documentation.\n    95→2. There are no third-party reviews on G2, Capterra, KLAS, or similar platforms.\n    96→3. The vendor website (mendelsonortho.com) redirects to the clinical practice's site (synergyhealth.org), which focuses on patient-facing information and says nothing about the EMR.\n    97→4. The developer (Proactive Technology Management) does not mention OrthoplexEMR on its own website.\n    98→5. The only technical documentation available is the ONC mandatory disclosures page and the EHI export page.\n    99→\n   100→The product's scope and data coverage must therefore be inferred primarily from its ONC certification criteria, required dependencies, and the clinical context of a large multi-site orthopedic practice group with surgery centers, imaging, PT/OT, and pain management services.\n   101→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. The practice has grown from a small family orthopedic office specializing in spine, neck, and back pain into a large musculoskeletal care organization with over 20 physicians across multiple locations (Livonia, Sterling Heights, Southfield, Port Huron, and others). The practice has rebranded under the umbrella of **Synergy Health Partners** (SHP), which is described as \"Michigan's only integrated musculoskeletal care provider.\" MKO remains the premier orthopedic practice within SHP. The Mendelson family continues in leadership — three sons of the founder (David, Jeffrey, and Stephen Mendelson) are orthopedic surgeons who co-own and manage the practice along with Dr. Martin Kornblum.\n\nOrthoplexEMR is a **custom-built, single-organization EMR** — it was developed specifically for MKO/SHP and is not a commercially sold product. The mandatory disclosures page explicitly states \"there are currently no plans for its sale.\" The EMR was built by **Proactive Technology Management**, a small managed IT services company based in Bingham Farms, Michigan (Metro Detroit), which is co-founded and owned by **Michael Weinberger**. Weinberger serves as CTO of both Proactive Technology Management and Synergy Health Partners MSO, LLC, making him the technical architect for both the IT infrastructure and the EMR. The CHPL contact, **Jurgen B. Jansen** (jjansen@synergyhealth.org), is an IT Project Manager at SynergyHealth. This is an unusually tight coupling between a clinical practice, its IT services provider, and its certified EMR — essentially an in-house software project.\n\n## Product: OrthoplexEMR\n\nCHPL ID: 9349\nCHPL Product Number: 15.04.04.3014.Orth.01.00.1.180101\nCertification Date: 2018-01-01\n\n### What It Is\n\nOrthoplexEMR is a proprietary, custom-built electronic medical records application developed by Proactive Technology Management for use exclusively by Mendelson Kornblum Orthopedic & Spine Specialists / Synergy Health Partners. It is certified as a complete Health IT Module with a broad set of ONC certifications covering clinical data management, care transitions, patient portal, public health reporting, and FHIR APIs.\n\nThe certified product is the entire EMR — there is no separate commercial product suite. The SED (Safety-enhanced Design) intended user description is simply \"Orthopedic Clinc\" [sic], confirming the narrow target audience.\n\n### Users & Market\n\n- **Single customer**: MKO/Synergy Health Partners. This is not a commercial EMR product.\n- **End users**: Orthopedic surgeons, spine specialists, pain management physicians, podiatrists, and clinical staff at MKO/SHP locations across Southeast Michigan.\n- **Setting**: Multi-site orthopedic practice group with 20+ physicians, including outpatient clinics, physical/occupational therapy sites, MRI imaging centers, and ambulatory surgery centers.\n- **No commercial market**: The disclosure page states there are no plans to sell the software.\n\n### Modules & Functionality\n\nBecause OrthoplexEMR is a custom in-house product, there is very limited public documentation of its features beyond what can be inferred from its ONC certification criteria and required dependencies. The product does not have a marketing website, feature pages, or third-party reviews.\n\n**What the certification criteria tell us:**\n- **(a)(1)–(a)(5)**: CPOE for medications, labs, imaging; drug-drug/drug-allergy interaction checks; demographics; vital signs; problem list — standard clinical documentation capabilities\n- **(a)(12)**: Family health history\n- **(a)(14)**: Implantable device list — particularly relevant for an orthopedic practice performing joint replacements\n- **(b)(1)–(b)(3)**: Transitions of care, clinical information reconciliation — C-CDA document generation and consumption\n- **(b)(10)–(b)(11)**: EHI export and care plan functionality\n- **(c)(1)–(c)(3)**: Clinical quality measures — specifically CMS50v6, CMS68v7, CMS123v6, CMS134v6, CMS138v6, CMS139v6 (covering referrals, medication documentation, diabetes care, chronic kidney disease, tobacco, and falls screening)\n- **(e)(1), (e)(3)**: Patient portal / view-download-transmit; patient health information capture\n- **(f)(1), (f)(4)**: Immunization registry and syndromic surveillance public health reporting\n- **(g)(3)–(g)(7), (g)(9)–(g)(10)**: Safety-enhanced design, quality management, accessibility, consolidated CDA creation, application access, and FHIR API access\n- **(h)(1)**: Direct Project messaging\n\n**Required dependencies (from mandatory disclosures):**\n- **MDToolbox**: E-prescribing module (electronic prescribing, EPCS, prior authorization). This tells us prescribing workflows are not native to OrthoplexEMR — they use MDToolbox as an integrated third-party service.\n- **EMRDirect**: Direct messaging HISP service for secure clinical data exchange (C-CDA transmission). This handles the (h)(1) Direct Project requirements.\n- **e-IMO (Intelligent Medical Objects)**: Clinical terminology and vocabulary service. IMO provides clinician-friendly diagnosis terms mapped to ICD, SNOMED CT, and other code sets. This means the system uses IMO for problem list, diagnosis coding, and likely billing code selection.\n- **SMTP (generic)**: Email integration for notifications and secure messaging.\n\n**What the EHI export page reveals about system content:**\nThe EHI export documentation describes C-CDA–based exports containing: demographics, encounters, medications, problems, allergies/adverse reactions, vital signs, care team information, immunizations, social history, medical equipment, test results, procedures, goals, health concerns, and treatment plans. This suggests these are the core clinical data domains the system manages.\n\n### Data & Content\n\nBased on the evidence gathered, OrthoplexEMR stores and manages:\n\n**Clinical data (confirmed by certification + EHI export page):**\n- Patient demographics\n- Problem lists / diagnoses (using IMO terminology mapped to ICD/SNOMED)\n- Medication lists and prescribing data (via MDToolbox integration)\n- Allergy and adverse reaction records\n- Vital signs\n- Encounter records\n- Procedures\n- Test/lab results\n- Immunization records\n- Social history\n- Medical equipment / implantable devices (especially relevant for orthopedic implants)\n- Care team information\n- Goals, health concerns, and treatment plans\n- Family health history\n- Clinical quality measure data\n\n**Likely stored but not directly confirmed from public sources:**\n- Clinical notes and documentation (implied by EMR use in a 20+ physician practice)\n- Imaging orders and possibly results (certified for CPOE imaging orders; MKO operates MRI centers)\n- Referral data (CMS50v6 is a referral measure)\n- Patient portal messages and patient-submitted health information (certified for (e)(1) and (e)(3))\n- Documents exchanged via Direct messaging (via EMRDirect)\n\n**Unclear / not confirmed:**\n- **Billing and claims data**: The website and disclosures do not mention whether OrthoplexEMR includes billing/practice management functionality. Michael Weinberger's bio mentions expertise in \"medical billing, scheduling, and credentialing systems,\" and the intake portal (intake.mendelsonortho.com) exists as a separate system, suggesting the practice may use separate systems for scheduling, billing, and intake. It is unclear whether these functions are part of OrthoplexEMR or handled by separate software.\n- **Scheduling**: The practice has a separate intake portal; scheduling may be separate from the EMR.\n- **Imaging/PACS**: MKO operates MRI centers, but whether PACS data is integrated into OrthoplexEMR or managed separately is unknown.\n- **Surgical records**: As an orthopedic surgery practice with ambulatory surgery centers, operative notes and surgical records are presumably part of the EMR, but this is not documented publicly.\n- **Physical/occupational therapy records**: SHP includes PT/OT services; whether those notes are in OrthoplexEMR or a separate system is unknown.\n\n### Research Gaps\n\nThis is an exceptionally difficult product to research because:\n1. It is a custom in-house EMR with no commercial presence, marketing materials, or public feature documentation.\n2. There are no third-party reviews on G2, Capterra, KLAS, or similar platforms.\n3. The vendor website (mendelsonortho.com) redirects to the clinical practice's site (synergyhealth.org), which focuses on patient-facing information and says nothing about the EMR.\n4. The developer (Proactive Technology Management) does not mention OrthoplexEMR on its own website.\n5. The only technical documentation available is the ONC mandatory disclosures page and the EHI export page.\n\nThe product's scope and data coverage must therefore be inferred primarily from its ONC certification criteria, required dependencies, and the clinical context of a large multi-site orthopedic practice group with surgery centers, imaging, PT/OT, and pain management services.\n","numLines":101,"startLine":1,"totalLines":101}}}

{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UKwcbbbT3mzbBAhCz61ghs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GNXwS9zXtQheuRxkE9LeAF","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/jmandel/hobby/ehi-export-analysis/results/mendelson-kornblum-orthopedic-spine-specialists/ehi-export-report.md","content":"# Mendelson Kornblum Orthopedic & Spine Specialists — EHI Export Documentation\n\nCollected: 2026-02-14\n\n## Source\n- Registered URL: https://orthoplex.mkoss.com/UserContent/Healthinformationexport.html\n- CHPL IDs: 9349\n- Product: OrthoplexEMR V1\n- Developer: Mendelson Kornblum Orthopedic & Spine Specialists (built by Proactive Technology Management)\n\n## Navigation Journal\n\n1. **Initial probe** — HTTP HEAD request to the registered URL:\n   ```bash\n   curl -sI -L \"https://orthoplex.mkoss.com/UserContent/Healthinformationexport.html\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0'\n   ```\n   Result: HTTP 200, `Content-Type: text/html`, 5200 bytes, served by Microsoft-IIS/10.0. Last-Modified: 2023-09-15. No redirects.\n\n2. **Page download**:\n   ```bash\n   curl -sL \"https://orthoplex.mkoss.com/UserContent/Healthinformationexport.html\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0' -o downloads/Healthinformationexport.html\n   ```\n   The page is a simple, unstyled HTML document (no CSS, no JavaScript, no images) containing all the EHI export documentation on a single page.\n\n3. **Link analysis** — The page contains exactly two outbound links:\n   - `http://www.hl7.org/ccdasearch/templates/2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.1.2.html` — HL7 C-CDA template reference (external standard; not downloaded per instructions)\n   - `https://portal.mendelsonortho.com/` — Patient portal login for patient self-service download (login-gated; noted but not downloaded)\n\n4. **Domain root check**:\n   ```bash\n   curl -sI \"https://orthoplex.mkoss.com/\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0'\n   ```\n   Redirects to `/Account/Login` — this is the OrthoplexEMR application login. The EHI export page is a static HTML file served from the `/UserContent/` directory of the application, publicly accessible without authentication.\n\n5. **Mandatory disclosures page** (`https://proactivemgmt.com/disclosure/`) was checked but contains no additional EHI export documentation — it's the Proactive Technology Management company site with standard ONC disclosure information.\n\n6. **Screenshot** taken of the full page in browser.\n\n## What Was Found\n\nThe entire EHI export documentation is a **single static HTML page** (5,200 bytes). There are no linked downloadable files (no PDFs, ZIPs, schemas, CSVs, or sample data). The page has not been updated since September 15, 2023.\n\n### Export Mechanism\n\nThe export is **C-CDA document generation**. Two export methods are described:\n\n1. **Single Patient Export** — Provider logs into OrthoplexEMR, searches for a patient, navigates to History → CCDA, and can:\n   - Download a ZIP file containing the C-CDA document (with optional encryption)\n   - Send via secure email\n   - Send via Direct messaging (requires a valid Direct mailbox address)\n\n2. **Patient Population Export** — Provider navigates to Utilities → CCDA, creates a named export job with configurable parameters:\n   - **Frequency**: Run Once, Daily, Weekly, Monthly, Yearly\n   - **Range**: Optional date start/end boundaries\n   - **Type**: All Patients or Single Patient\n   - Output is placed on a shared server accessible within the MKO network or via SynergyHealth VPN\n\n3. **Patient Self-Service Download** — Patients log into the portal at `portal.mendelsonortho.com` and access \"Patient Summary for Transition of Care\" to download their own data.\n\n### Data Dictionary\n\nThe page lists 16 C-CDA sections with their field elements:\n\n| Section | Fields |\n|---------|--------|\n| Demographics | First Name, Last Name, DOB, Sex, Race, Preferred Language, Ethnicity (primary/secondary), Contact Info, Patient ID |\n| Document | Document ID, Created Date, Author, Contact Info |\n| Encounter | Encounter ID, Encounter Date, Responsible Party, Contact Info |\n| Document Meta | Maintained by, Contact Info |\n| Medications | Medication, Code, Type, Strength, Dose, Route, Frequency, Date Started, Status |\n| Problems | Problem Code, Patient Problem, Status, Date Diagnosed |\n| Allergies/Adverse Reactions/Alerts | Allergy Code, Substance, Medication/Agent Allergy, Reaction, Date Entered |\n| Vital Signs | Date/Time, Height, Weight, Blood Pressure, Pulse, Temp, Resp, Pulse Ox, O2 % BldC Ox, Inhaled Ox Conc |\n| Care Team Information | Name, Position, Email |\n| Immunizations | Empty (noted: \"Immunizations not provided at clinics\") |\n| Social History (smoking) | Smoking Code, Smoking Status, from/to |\n| Medical Equipment | Description, Date and Time, Status |\n| Results (Tests) | Code, Code System, Name, Date, Result, Lab, Provider |\n| Procedures | Description, Date and Time, Status |\n| Goals | (free form) |\n| Health Concerns | (free form) |\n| Plan of Treatment | Plan of Treatment, Assessment |\n| Reason for Referral | (free form) |\n\nThe \"Structure of Export\" section simply links to the HL7 C-CDA Continuity of Care Document template (2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.1.2).\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\n\nThis export is a **standard C-CDA patient summary** — it covers the clinical data domains one would expect in a Continuity of Care Document, which aligns closely with USCDI / US Core data classes. Based on the product research, here is the coverage picture:\n\n**Clearly covered:**\n- Patient demographics\n- Problem lists / diagnoses\n- Medications\n- Allergies and adverse reactions\n- Vital signs\n- Encounters (ID, date, responsible party only)\n- Care team\n- Procedures (description-level only)\n- Test/lab results\n- Social history (smoking status only)\n- Medical equipment / implantable devices\n- Goals, health concerns, treatment plans (free-form text)\n- Referral reasons (free-form text)\n\n**Explicitly absent (noted by vendor):**\n- Immunizations — the page states \"Immunizations not provided at clinics,\" which is plausible for an orthopedic specialty practice\n\n**Likely stored but NOT covered by this export:**\n- **Clinical notes and documentation** — A 20+ physician orthopedic practice generates extensive clinical notes (history & physical, operative notes, progress notes, consult notes). None are mentioned in the export. This is a major gap.\n- **Imaging orders and results** — MKO operates MRI centers; imaging orders are certified under (a)(4). Not in the export.\n- **Surgical/operative records** — An orthopedic surgery practice with ambulatory surgery centers. Operative notes, surgical details, implant records beyond the \"Medical Equipment\" section are not documented.\n- **Billing and claims data** — Whether in OrthoplexEMR or a separate system, billing data is not mentioned.\n- **Scheduling data** — Appointment history, no-shows, scheduling patterns.\n- **Patient portal messages** — Certified for (e)(1) and (e)(3); patient-submitted health information is not in the export.\n- **Direct messaging documents** — Documents received via EMRDirect.\n- **Family health history** — Certified for (a)(12) but not listed in the export sections.\n- **Clinical quality measure data** — Certified for (c)(1)-(c)(3).\n- **Audit logs** — No mention.\n- **Physical/occupational therapy records** — SHP includes PT/OT services.\n- **Custom forms or specialty-specific data** — Orthopedic assessment tools, pain scales, functional outcome measures.\n\n**Assessment**: This is a **C-CDA patient summary, not a comprehensive EHI export**. It covers approximately the same data as a (g)(10) FHIR US Core API would — the standard clinical summary domains. It does not attempt to export \"all electronic health information\" as required by (b)(10). The export format (C-CDA CCD) is inherently a summary document format, not a bulk data export format. Critical data domains like clinical notes, imaging, surgical records, and billing are absent.\n\n### Export Format & Standards\n\n- **Format**: C-CDA (Consolidated Clinical Document Architecture), specifically the Continuity of Care Document (CCD) template (2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.1.2)\n- **Standard**: HL7 C-CDA — a recognized healthcare interoperability standard\n- **Delivery**: ZIP file download, secure email, or Direct messaging (single patient); shared server file drop (population export)\n- **Appropriateness**: C-CDA is appropriate for clinical summary exchange but is **not appropriate as a comprehensive EHI export format**. It cannot represent billing data, audit logs, imaging data, custom forms, or many other data types that an orthopedic EMR stores. A C-CDA CCD is fundamentally a summary — it's the right format for transitions of care, not for \"export everything.\"\n\nThe population export feature with scheduling (daily/weekly/monthly/yearly) is a useful operational feature, but the underlying data scope remains the same C-CDA summary regardless of how many patients are exported.\n\n### Documentation Quality\n\n- **Readability**: The page is simple and readable, though unstyled. The instructions are clear step-by-step guides.\n- **Data dictionary**: Present but minimal — lists section names and field names only. No data types, no value sets, no cardinality, no constraints, no coding system details beyond the generic \"Code\" fields.\n- **Examples**: None. No sample C-CDA documents, no sample data.\n- **Developer usability**: A developer could not implement an import based solely on this documentation. They would need to rely on the generic C-CDA specification and reverse-engineer any vendor-specific patterns from actual export files.\n- **Maintenance**: The page was last modified September 15, 2023. The product was certified in 2018. The documentation appears to be a static compliance artifact.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n\n- **Granularity**: Section-level with field names only. No data types, no descriptions of what each field contains, no cardinality (required vs. optional), no constraints.\n- **Coded fields**: Several sections mention \"Code\" fields (Medication Code, Problem Code, Allergy Code, Smoking Code, Code System) but do not specify which code systems are used (ICD-10, SNOMED CT, RxNorm, etc.) or provide value sets. The product research notes they use e-IMO (Intelligent Medical Objects) for clinical terminology, but this isn't documented.\n- **Relationships**: No documentation of how entities relate to each other beyond what's implicit in C-CDA structure.\n- **Versioning**: No version history or change tracking.\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nThis is a **minimal compliance documentation effort** from a custom, single-organization EMR. The export itself is a standard C-CDA patient summary — functionally equivalent to a transitions-of-care document rather than a true (b)(10) \"all EHI\" export. For an orthopedic surgery practice with imaging centers, ASCs, PT/OT, and pain management, the C-CDA summary format misses large swaths of clinically and operationally important data.\n\nThe documentation is honest in what it describes (note the candid \"Immunizations: Empty\" entry), but the scope of what it exports is narrow. The page links to the generic C-CDA CCD template rather than providing vendor-specific profile documentation or sample files.\n\nGiven that OrthoplexEMR is a custom in-house system with no commercial customers and development by a small IT firm, the minimal documentation is not surprising but is still notable. The (b)(10) requirement applies regardless of whether a product is commercial or single-organization.\n\n## Access Summary\n- Final URL (after redirects): https://orthoplex.mkoss.com/UserContent/Healthinformationexport.html\n- Status: found\n- Required browser: no (static HTML, no JavaScript required)\n- Navigation complexity: direct_link\n- Anti-bot issues: none\n\n## Obstacles & Dead Ends\n- No obstacles encountered. The page loaded directly via curl with no authentication, no JavaScript, and no anti-bot measures.\n- The domain root (`orthoplex.mkoss.com`) requires login — it's the EMR application. Only the `/UserContent/` path is publicly accessible.\n- The mandatory disclosures site (`proactivemgmt.com/disclosure/`) was checked but contains no additional EHI export documentation.\n- No downloadable files (PDF, ZIP, schema, sample data) exist — the entire documentation is the single HTML page.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1232,"cache_read_input_tokens":51901,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1232},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"307a26dd-62f9-490a-b8f3-eb112e9cec3f","uuid":"421a019f-9e2c-4116-be82-65f8e366207f"}
